Definitions for All

  • Deterministic Finite Automaton (DFA): A DFA MMM is a machine that reads a finite-length string one symbol at a time in one pass, transitions from state to state, and ultimately accepts or rejects. Formally, MMM is a 5-tuple M=(Q,Σ,δ,q0,F)M = (Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_0, F)M=(Q,Σ,δ,q0​,F), where

    • QQQ is a finite, non-empty set of states;

    • Σ\SigmaΣ is the finite, non-empty alphabet;

    • δ:Q×Σ→Q\delta: Q \times \Sigma \rightarrow Qδ:Q×Σ→Q is the transition function;

    • q0∈Qq_0 \in Qq0​∈Q is the starting state;

    • F⊆QF \subseteq QF⊆Q is the set of accepting states;

  • Given a DFA MMM, L(M)L(M)L(M) denotes the set of strings that the DFA accepts.

  • Regular language: A language LLL is regular if L=L(M)L = L(M)L=L(M) for some DFA MMM (MMM solves LLL).

  • If L1L_1L1​ and L2L_2L2​ are both regular languages over Σ∗\Sigma^*Σ∗, for some fixed Σ\SigmaΣ, then the following are all regular:

    • L1‾=Σ∗∖L1\overline{L_1} = \Sigma^* \setminus L_1L1​​=Σ∗∖L1​,

    • L1∪L2L_1 \cup L_2L1​∪L2​,

    • L1∩L2L_1 \cap L_2L1​∩L2​,

    • L1L2L_1 L_2L1​L2​ (the concatenation of two regular languages),

    • L1∗L_1^*L1∗​ (this is an exercise in the textbook; not an easy one though).

Odd Ones Out

Draw a DFA that decides the language L={x:x has an even number of 1s and an odd number of 0s}L = \{x: \text{$x$ has an even number of 1s and an odd number of 0s}\}L={x:x has an even number of 1s and an odd number of 0s} over the alphabet Σ={0,1}\Sigma = \{{\texttt{0}}, {\texttt{1}}\}Σ={0,1}.

Solution
Solution

We have 444 states with the following meanings. The string we have seen so far has:

  • even number of 0{\texttt{0}}0’s and even number of 1{\texttt{1}}1’s (state q0q_0q0​);

  • even number of 0{\texttt{0}}0’s and odd number of 1{\texttt{1}}1’s (state q1q_1q1​);

  • odd number of 0{\texttt{0}}0’s and even number of 1{\texttt{1}}1’s (state q2q_2q2​);

  • odd number of 0{\texttt{0}}0’s and odd number of 1{\texttt{1}}1’s (state q3q_3q3​).

4
Adam, I’m Ada!

Show that, if ∣Σ∣>1\lvert \Sigma \rvert > 1∣Σ∣>1, then L={x∣x∈Σ∗ and x=xR}L = \{x \mid x \in \Sigma^* \text{ and } x = x^R \}L={x∣x∈Σ∗ and x=xR} is a non-regular language.

Solution
Solution

Any string xxx that satisfies x=xRx = x^Rx=xR is called a palindrome.

As usual, we will prove that the language is non-regular by a proof by contradiction and apply the pigeonhole principle (PHP). So assume for the sake of contradiction that there exists a DFA with kkk states that solves LLL. Consider two distinct symbols a,b∈Σa,b \in \Sigmaa,b∈Σ (since we assumed ∣Σ∣>1|\Sigma| > 1∣Σ∣>1). Consider the k+1k+1k+1 strings bnab^nabna for n∈{0,…,k}n \in \{0, \ldots, k\}n∈{0,…,k}. Since there are only kkk states, by PHP, there must exist some i,ji,ji,j, 0≤i<j≤k0 \leq i < j \leq k0≤i<j≤k, such that biab^iabia and bjab^jabja end up in the same state. Thus, biabib^iab^ibiabi and bjabib^jab^ibjabi must end up in the same state. However, biabib^iab^ibiabi is a palindrome, so it should end up in an accepting state, and bjabib^jab^ibjabi is not a palindrome, so it should end up in a rejecting state. This is the desired contradiction since a state cannot be both accepting and rejecting.

5
Suffering with Suffixes

Given a word www, we say that uuu is a proper suffix of www if there is v≠ϵv \neq \epsilonv=ϵ such that w=vuw = vuw=vu. For a language LLL, define SUFF(L)={w∈L:no proper suffix of w is in L}.\text{SUFF}(L) = \{w \in L : \text{no proper suffix of $w$ is in $L$}\}.SUFF(L)={w∈L:no proper suffix of w is in L}. Show that if LLL is regular, then so is SUFF(L)\text{SUFF}(L)SUFF(L), as follows. Give an exact description of a DFA solving SUFF(L)\text{SUFF}(L)SUFF(L), explicitly stating how QQQ, δ\deltaδ, q0q_0q0​ and FFF are defined. Furthermore, briefly explain the reasoning behind your construction. A detailed proof of correctness is not needed.

Solution
Solution

The construction is very similar to the construction we have seen for showing regular languages are closed under the concatenation operation. In that proof, we opened up a thread every time we encountered an accepting state of the first machine. In this case, we will open up a new thread after reading each symbol. We now give the details.

Since LLL is regular, we know that there is some DFA M=(Q,Σ,δ,q0,F)M = (Q, \Sigma, \delta, q_0, F)M=(Q,Σ,δ,q0​,F) that solves LLL. Recall that for S⊆QS \subseteq QS⊆Q and σ∈Σ\sigma \in \Sigmaσ∈Σ, we let δ℘(S,σ)={δ(s,σ):s∈S}\delta_{\wp}(S, \sigma) = \{\delta(s, \sigma) : s \in S\}δ℘​(S,σ)={δ(s,σ):s∈S}. Now, we define M′=(Q′,Σ,δ′,q0′,F′)M' = (Q', \Sigma, \delta', q_0', F')M′=(Q′,Σ,δ′,q0′​,F′) that solves SUFF(L)\text{SUFF}(L)SUFF(L) as follows:

  • Q′=Q×℘(Q)Q' = Q \times \wp(Q)Q′=Q×℘(Q)

  • For any q∈Qq \in Qq∈Q, S⊆QS \subseteq QS⊆Q, and σ∈Σ\sigma \in \Sigmaσ∈Σ, define δ′((q,S),σ)=(δ(q,σ),δ℘(S,σ)∪{q0})\delta'((q, S), \sigma) = (\delta(q, \sigma), \delta_{\wp}(S, \sigma) \cup \{q_0\})δ′((q,S),σ)=(δ(q,σ),δ℘​(S,σ)∪{q0​})

  • q0′=(q0,∅)q_0' = (q_0, \varnothing)q0′​=(q0​,∅)

  • F′={(q,S):q∈F,S∩F=∅}F' = \{(q, S) : q \in F, S \cap F = \varnothing\}F′={(q,S):q∈F,S∩F=∅}

Intuitively, the first component of the state tuple (in M′M'M′) keeps track of ‘the main thread’ (i.e. the computation of the DFA on the whole string), while the second component keeps track of all the ‘suffix threads’ (i.e. the computation of the DFA on proper suffixes of the whole string). The transition function is defined with this design in mind. At each character, the main thread and each of the suffix threads takes one step; additionally, a new suffix thread is started. In the end, we accept if and only if the main thread has accepted and all the suffix threads have rejected.

6
States for Days (Extra Problem)

The state complexity of a language is the minimum number of states in any DFA solving the language. If a language is non-regular, then we define the state complexity to be infinity.

To show that a language is non-regular, we have seen a proof strategy that can be viewed as showing that the state complexity of the non-regular language is infinity. It turns out, the same kind of argument can be applied to regular languages to show a lower bound on the state complexity of the language. In this problem, our goal will be to illustrate this.

For any k≥1k \ge 1k≥1, let Rk={x∣x∈{0,1}∗ and the k-th symbol from the right is a 1}.R_k = \left\{ x \mid x\in \{{\texttt{0}}, {\texttt{1}}\}^* \text{ and the $k$-th symbol from the right is a {\texttt{1}}} \right\}.Rk​={x∣x∈{0,1}∗ and the k-th symbol from the right is a 1}. Show that any DFA that solves RkR_kRk​ must have at least 2k2^k2k states.

Solution
Solution

Fix an arbitrary k≥1k \geq 1k≥1. We will show that any DFA solving RkR_kRk​ must have at least 2k2^k2k states. To do this, we will identify 2k2^k2k strings such that in any DFA solving the language, these 2k2^k2k strings, when fed into the DFA, must end up in different states.

Consider the set BkB_kBk​ of all binary strings of length kkk. Note that ∣Bk∣=2k|B_k|=2^k∣Bk​∣=2k. We claim that in any DFA solving RkR_kRk​, the strings in BkB_kBk​ must end up in different states. To prove this, assume for the sake of contradiction that there are two strings xxx and yyy that end up in the same state. Since x≠yx \neq yx=y, there is some iii such that xi≠yix_i \neq y_ixi​=yi​. Let’s now consider the strings x′=x0ix' = x{\texttt{0}}^{i}x′=x0i and y′=y0iy' = y{\texttt{0}}^{i}y′=y0i. Observe that in x′x'x′ and y′y'y′, the bits xix_ixi​ and yiy_iyi​ are the kkk’th characters from the right. Since xxx and yyy end up in the same state, and we append the same string 0i{\texttt{0}}^i0i to both to obtain x′x'x′ and y′y'y′, we know x′x'x′ and y′y'y′ must end up in the same state. However, since xi≠yix_i \neq y_ixi​=yi​, one of x′x'x′ and y′y'y′ ends up in an accepting state, and the other in a rejecting state. This is the desired contradiction.

Regular Expressions (Extra Problem)

As mentioned in class, regular languages can be defined recursively/inductively as follows:

  • ∅\varnothing∅ is regular.

  • {a}\{a\}{a} for each a∈Σa \in \Sigmaa∈Σ is regular.

  • If L1L_1L1​ and L2L_2L2​ are regular, then L1∪L2L_1 \cup L_2L1​∪L2​ is regular.

  • If L1L_1L1​ and L2L_2L2​ are regular, then L1L2L_1 L_2L1​L2​ is regular.

  • If LLL is regular, then L∗L^*L∗ is regular.

Often, regular languages are represented compactly using what is known as a regular expression. We define regular expressions inductively as follows:

  • Any single string is a regular expression (representing the singleton set containing that string).

  • If AAA and BBB are regular expressions, then (A+B)(A+B)(A+B) is a regular expression (representing the union of AAA and BBB).

  • If AAA and BBB are regular expressions, then (AB)(AB)(AB) is a regular expression (representing the concatenation of AAA and BBB).

  • If AAA is a regular expression, then A∗A^*A∗ is the regular expression.

Noting the correspondence between the two inductive definitions above, a language is regular if and only if it can be represented by a regular expression.

Here are a few shortcuts related to regular expressions. We use Σ\SigmaΣ to denote the regular expression corresponding to taking the union of all strings of length 111. So if Σ={0,1}\Sigma = \{{\texttt{0}}, {\texttt{1}}\}Σ={0,1} then Σ\SigmaΣ would denote (0+1)({\texttt{0}} + {\texttt{1}})(0+1). We also use AkA^kAk to denote the regular expression corresponding to taking the concatenation of AAA with itself kkk times. Parentheses in regular expressions can be omitted to reduce clutter, provided the removal does not introduce any ambiguity.

For the problems below, you do not need to provide justifications for your answers.

  1. Let Σ={0,1}\Sigma = \{{\texttt{0}}, {\texttt{1}}\}Σ={0,1}. For each regular expression below, describe in English the language it represents.

    • 1Σ∗{\texttt{1}}\Sigma^*1Σ∗

    • Σ∗101Σ∗\Sigma^* {\texttt{101}} \Sigma^*Σ∗101Σ∗

    • 1(00)∗1{\texttt{1}}({\texttt{00}})^*{\texttt{1}}1(00)∗1

    • (Σ251)∗(\Sigma^{251})^*(Σ251)∗

  2. Let Σ={a,b}\Sigma = \{{\texttt{a}}, {\texttt{b}}\}Σ={a,b}. Give a regular expression for the languages below.

    • The set of all strings with a single a{\texttt{a}}a.

    • The set of all strings that start and end with the same symbol.

    • The set of all strings that contain at least two a{\texttt{a}}a’s and at most one b{\texttt{b}}b.

    • The set of all strings containing an even number of a{\texttt{a}}a’s, an odd number of b{\texttt{b}}b’s, and not containing the substring ab{\texttt{ab}}ab.

Solution
Solution

    • The set of all strings that start with a 1{\texttt{1}}1.

    • The set of all strings that contain 101{\texttt{101}}101 as a substring.

    • The set of all even-length strings that have exactly two 1{\texttt{1}}1’s, one at the start of the string and one at the end.

    • The set of all strings whose length is a multiple of 251251251.

    • b∗ab∗{\texttt{b}}^*{\texttt{a}}{\texttt{b}}^*b∗ab∗

    • aΣ∗a+bΣ∗b+a+b{\texttt{a}}\Sigma^*{\texttt{a}} + {\texttt{b}}\Sigma^*{\texttt{b}} + {\texttt{a}} + {\texttt{b}}aΣ∗a+bΣ∗b+a+b

    • aa∗a+aaa∗ba∗+aa∗ba∗a+a∗ba∗aa{\texttt{aa}}^*{\texttt{a}} + {\texttt{aa}}{\texttt{a}}^*{\texttt{b}}{\texttt{a}}^* + {\texttt{a}}{\texttt{a}}^*{\texttt{b}}{\texttt{a}}^*{\texttt{a}} + {\texttt{a}}^*{\texttt{b}}{\texttt{a}}^*{\texttt{a}}{\texttt{a}}aa∗a+aaa∗ba∗+aa∗ba∗a+a∗ba∗aa

Multiple Multiples (Bonus)

Let Σ={0,1}\Sigma = \{{\texttt{0}}, {\texttt{1}}\}Σ={0,1}. Define C3={x∈Σ∗:x is a binary number that is a multiple of 3}.C_3 = \{x \in \Sigma^* : x \text{ is a binary number that is a multiple of } 3\}.C3​={x∈Σ∗:x is a binary number that is a multiple of 3}. Show that C3C_3C3​ is regular.

Solution
Solution

Our set of states will be Q={q0,q1,q2}Q = \{q_0, q_1, q_2\}Q={q0​,q1​,q2​} corresponding to the possible remainders modulo 333. We want the following property to hold: a string corresponding to the binary representation of a number www should end on state qiq_iqi​ if w≡i(mod3)w \equiv i \pmod 3w≡i(mod3). If we can establish this, then we can set F={q0}F = \{q_0\}F={q0​}.

As we read a binary string sss, we can determine what number/value it corresponds to as follows: Start with value 000. Scan sss from left to right. If we see a 0{\texttt{0}}0, multiply the value by 2. If we see a 1{\texttt{1}}1, multiply the value by 2 and add 1. (Take a moment to verify that this is true.)

With this observation in mind, we’ll define our transition function as follows. δ(qi,0)=q2i,\delta(q_i, {\texttt{0}}) = q_{2i},δ(qi​,0)=q2i​, and δ(qi,1)=q2i+1\delta(q_i, {\texttt{1}}) = q_{2i+1}δ(qi​,1)=q2i+1​, where indices of the qqq’s are taken modulo 333.

We leave the following as exercises for you: (i) Why is the above transition function correct? (ii) Does the argument generalize to mod values other than 333?
